I bet it can also be an XSS attack vector. Imagine that there is some piece of jQuery-based code that evaluates selectors based on the ID attribute of a given element (e.g. for this element find all the related ones):<p><pre><code>  $('.' + div.attr('id')).each(function() {
      $('body').append($(this); // Moving elements
  });
</code></pre>
Now imagine that I give the id attribute the following id: 'nada,<script src="evil.js"></script>'<p>I suppose this is a bit contrived but still fun.
